Employment Prediction 2022 in Berlin¶

Paula Moyano Sánchez¶

Data: the data for this project comes from the open data source of Berlin Brandenburg here. Currently the spreadsheet is not available on the website.

Motivation: the estimation can be especially interesting regarding the influence of COVID-19 pandemic in the last few years.

Objective: in this project we are going to predict the number of employed persons in Germany based on the number of employees from 1991 to 2020.

Import packages¶

First we import the key data analysis modules

Our original dataframe direclty extracted from the spreadsheet contains 'Erwerbstätige insgesamt' as the the total number of employees pro year distributed as:

  1. 'Land- und Forstwirtschaft, Fischerei',
  2. 'Produzierendes Gewerbe',
    • 'Produzierendes Gewerbe (ohne Baugewerbe)',
    • 'Baugewerbe',
  3. 'Dienstleistungsbereiche'
    • 'Handel, Verkehr, Gastgewerbe, Information\n und Kommunikation',
    • 'Finanz-,Versicherungs- u. Unternehmensdienstleister, \n Grundstücks- u. Wohnungswesen',
    • 'Öffentliche und sonstige Dienstleister, \n Erziehung, Gesundheit'

We will split into the categories important for our analysis. We change our dataframe into English and split these data creating new datasets

Create splited dataframes¶

As mentioned before, this dataframe comprehends the total number of workers in Berlin between 1991 and 2020 divided in categories and subcategories as below:

  1. 'Agriculture_forestry_fishing',
  2. 'Industry',
    • 'Industry_without_construction',
    • 'Manufacturing', 'Construction',
  3. 'Services',
    • 'Commerce_transport_hospitality_information_communication',
    • 'Finance_insurance_corporate_realestate_housing',
    • 'Public_services_education_health'
  1. First we create a dataset with the three categories of economic sectors with the sum of the total of workers, and its transposed

# Create a data frame with the 3 sectors of interest for the histogram 

df_top3_hist = df_totals.loc[['Agriculture_forestry_fishing', 'Industry', 'Services'], years]

df_top3_hist.head(3)

# df_top3_hist = df_top3_hist.astype(int)

count, bin_edges = np.histogram(df_top3_hist, 15) # get the x-tick values

# Adjust the min and max x-axis labels to remove the extra gap on the edges of the plot
xmin = bin_edges[0] - 10   #  first bin value is 0.0, adding buffer of 10 for aesthetic purposes 
xmax = bin_edges[-1] + 10  #  last bin value is 1838.0, adding buffer of 10 for aesthetic purposes

# Generate stacked histogram

df_top3_hist.plot(kind= "hist", 
             figsize=(7,5),
             bins=15, # Increase the bin size to 15 by passing in bins parameter
             alpha=0.6, # Set transparency to 60% by passing in alpha parameter
             xticks=bin_edges, # Get the x-tick values
             color=['coral', 'darkslateblue', 'mediumseagreen'], # change the colors of the plots by passing in color parameter
             stacked=True,
             xlim=(xmin, xmax),
             )  

plt.title('Histogram of 3 sectors of employment in Berlin 1991-2020') # add a title to the histogram
plt.ylabel('More contributive sectors to employment') # add y-label
plt.xlabel('Number of employees') # add x-label

Out[220]:
'No. employees = 13 * Year + -23859'

Since we are plotting a linear regression y= a*x + b, our output has 2 elements [5.56709228e+03, -1.09261952e+07] with:

slope in position 0
intercept in position 1

And it doesn´t work because our study case it´s not a linear regression

Using the equation of line of best fit, we can estimate the number of employees for 2022:

  • No. Immigrants = 13 * Year - 23850
  • No. Immigrants = 13 * 2021 - 23850
  • No. Immigrants = 2436

In 2020 the total of workers were 2058.631, that means 365 workers more in two years, so this linear regression prediction seems not to be accurate.

# Step 3. Plot the data 

# Industry (Produzierendes Gewerbe)

# ax parameter: passing it to plot two different scatter plots in one plot, 
# We include the axes of one plot into the other

# s parameter: to pass in the weights:
# Normalized weights are between 0-1, they won't be visible on the plot
# So we will multiply weights by 2000 to scale it up on the graph
# we will add 10 to compensate for the min value (which has a 0 weight so scale with x2000)

ax0 = df_totals_bubbleplot.plot(kind='scatter',
                    x='Year',
                    y='Industry',
                    figsize=(7,5),
                    alpha=0.5, # transparency
                    color='green',
                    s=norm_industry * 2000 + 10, # pass in weights 
                    xlim=(1991, 2020)
                   )

# Services (Dienstleistungsbereiche)
ax1 = df_totals_bubbleplot.plot(kind='scatter',
                    x='Year',
                    y='Services',
                    alpha=0.5,
                    color="blue",
                    s= norm_services * 2000 + 10,
                    ax = ax0
